Meanwhile, as the Trojans maintained their careful watch,\uc0\u8232 Panic, chilling Fear\'92s dread comrade, gripped Achaeans,\u8232 their best men suffering unendurable anguish.\u8232 Just like those times two winds blow in from Thrace\'97\u8232 North Wind and West Wind suddenly spring up\u8232 and lash the fish-filled seas\'97black waves at once rise up,\u8232 then fling seaweed in piles along the shoreline\'97\u8232 so spirits in Achaean chests were now cast down.\u8232 Atreus\'92 son, heart overwhelmed with painful sorrow,\u8232 went to give out orders for clear-voiced heralds\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a010\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[10]\u8232 to summon all the warriors to assembly,\u8232 calling them one by one, not with a general shout.\u8232 He himself, with his heralds, carried out the task.\u8232 The counsellors sat heart sick. Agamemnon stood,\u8232 his face shedding tears like a black water spring\u8232 whose dark stream flows down a sheer rock precipice.\u8232 With a sigh, Agamemnon addressed the Argives:\
\'93My friends, leaders, Argive counsellors,\uc0\u8232 Zeus, son of Cronos, has snared me badly\u8232 in grievous folly. Deceptive god,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a020\u8232 he promised me\'97he nodded his assent\'97\u8232 that I\'92d lay waste to well-built Ilion,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[20]\u8232 before I went back home. Now he tricks me\u8232 He\'92s devised a cruel deceit for me,\u8232 telling me to return to Argos in disgrace,\u8232 after the deaths of so many warriors.\u8232 That\'92s what now delights all-powerful Zeus,\u8232 who has hurled down so many lofty towns,\u8232 and who\'92ll still demolish many more\'97\u8232 such is his power, irresistible.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a030\u8232 But come, let\'92s all follow what I propose\'97\u8232 let\'92s sail back to our dear native land.\u8232 For we\'92re never going to capture Troy.\'94\
He finished. All those there stayed silent, stunned.\uc0\u8232 Achaea\'92s sons just sat there, speechless with grief.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[30]\u8232 At last Diomedes, skilled in battle cries, spoke out:\
\'93Son of Atreus, I\'92ll be the first to challenge\uc0\u8232 your foolishness, as is my right, my lord,\u8232 in our assembly. So don\'92t be angry.\u8232 First of all, you slighted my bravery\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a040\u8232 in front of all Danaans, when you claimed\u8232 I was no soldier, an unwarlike man.\u8232 Achaeans, young and old, all know this.\u8232 The son of crooked-minded Cronos gave you\u8232 a two-edged gift\'97he gave you honour\u8232 to govern all men with your sceptre,\u8232 but he didn\'92t give the strongest power,\u8232 courage. My misguided king, do you think\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[40]\u8232 Achaea\'92s sons are really fearful cowards,\u8232 as you state? If your heart wishes to go home,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a050\u8232 then go. The road lies there in front of you.\u8232 The many ships which sailed here with you\u8232 from Mycenae stand ready by the sea.\u8232 But the rest of the long-haired Achaeans\u8232 will stay here, until we demolish Troy.\u8232 If they flee back to their dear native land\u8232 in their ships, too, then Sthenelus and I\u8232 will fight on to our goal, to take Ilion.\u8232 For the gods were with us when we came.\'94\
With a roar, all Achaea\'92s sons endorsed his words,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a060\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[50]\uc0\u8232 pleased with the speech made by horse-taming Diomedes.\u8232 Then horseman Nestor, standing up before them, said:\
\'93Son of Tydeus, you\'92re excellent in battle\uc0\u8232 and the best Achaean of your age in council.\u8232 No Achaean will fault what you\'92ve just said\u8232 or oppose it. But your speech is incomplete.\u8232 You are still young\'97you might well be my son,\u8232 my youngest born. Still, you spoke sensibly,\u8232 in what you said to the Achaean king.\u8232 For you spoke justly and kept to the point.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a070\u8232 But come, I can claim to be your senior,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[60]\u8232 so I shall explain this matter fully.\u8232 Let no one take issue now with what I say,\u8232 not even mighty Agamemnon.\u8232 Any man who\'92s keen on civil war\u8232 is an evil outlaw, without a heart,\u8232 without a home. So for the time being,\u8232 now that night has come, let\'92s do what we must.\u8232 Let\'92s get dinner ready, something to eat.\u8232 And let\'92s have sentries camp beside that trench\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a080\u8232 we dug outside the wall. I\'92m saying young men\u8232 should do this. Then, issue your instructions,\u8232 son of Atreus, for you are chief king here.\u8232 Prepare a meal for senior counsellors\'97\u8232 that\'92s the right and proper thing to do.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[70]\u8232 You\'92ve got lots of wine stockpiled in your huts,\u8232 which Achaea\'92s sons bring here every day\u8232 over the wide sea from Thrace\'97you\'92ve got\u8232 all you need to show such hospitality,\u8232 for you are ruler over many men.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a090\u8232 Once many people have assembled there,\u8232 you should follow whoever offers you\u8232 the best advice. All we Achaeans need\u8232 good practical advice, especially now,\u8232 when enemies are burning many fires\u8232 right beside our ships. Who finds that pleasant?\u8232 This night saves our army or destroys it.\'94\
Nestor spoke. Those present listened carefully,\uc0\u8232 then followed what he\'92d said. Armed sentinels went out,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[80]\u8232 led by Thrasymedes, Nestor\'92s son, his people\'92s shepherd,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0100\u8232 with Ascalaphus and Ialmenus, strong fighters,\u8232 and Meriones, Aphareus, and De\'efpyrus,\u8232 along with noble Lycomedes, Creion\'92s son.\u8232 These seven were captains of the sentinels.\u8232 A hundred young men, all armed with their long spears,\u8232 went with each of them. They marched off and took positions\u8232 half way between the ditch and wall. Then the men lit fires\u8232 and prepared their meals. Atreus\'92 son led his advisors\u8232 to his hut and gave all of them a generous meal.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[90]\u8232 They ate the food prepared and set before them,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0110\u8232 and each man ate and drank to his full heart\'92s content.\u8232 Old Nestor, whose previous advice had seemed the best,\u8232 was the first to begin explaining what he thought.\u8232 Keeping in mind their common good, he spoke out:\
\'93Mighty son of Atreus, Agamemnon,\uc0\u8232 king of men, I\'92ll begin and end my speech\u8232 with you, for you are lord of many men.\u8232 Zeus gave you sceptre and laws to rule them.\u8232 Thus, you, above all, should speak and listen,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[100]\'a0\'a0\u8232 then act upon what other men may say,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0120\u8232 if their spirit prompts them to speak well.\u8232 You\'92ll get the credit for what they begin.\u8232 So I\'92ll say what seems to me the best advice.\u8232 No one else has set out a better scheme\u8232 than the one which I\'92ve been mulling over\u8232 a long time now, ever since you, my lord,\u8232 made Achilles angry by taking back\u8232 that young girl Briseis from his hut,\u8232 against my judgment. Repeatedly,\u8232 I urged you not to do it. But then you,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0130\u8232 surrendering to your arrogant spirit,\u8232 shamed our strongest man, honoured by the gods.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[110]\u8232 You still have that prize you took. So now let\'92s think\u8232 how we may make amends, win him back with gifts\u8232 and gracious speeches, and be friends once more.\'94\
Agamemnon, king of men, then answered Nestor:\
\'93Old man, you expose my folly justly.\uc0\u8232 I was deluded. I don\'92t deny that.\u8232 The man whom Zeus loves in his heart is worth\u8232 whole armies. And this man Zeus now honours\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0140\u8232 by destroying an army of Achaeans.\u8232 Since my delusion made me follow\u8232 my mistaken feelings, I\'92m now willing\u8232 to make amends, to give in recompense\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[120]\u8232 immense treasures. I\'92ll list these rich gifts\u8232 in presence of you all\'97seven tripods\u8232 which fire has not yet touched, ten gold talents,\u8232 twenty shining cauldrons, twelve strong horse\u8232 whose speed has triumphed and earned them prizes.\u8232 A man who has as much as I have won\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0150\u8232 from racing these sure-footed animals\u8232 would not be poor, or lack possessions,\u8232 or need precious gold. And then I\'92ll give him\u8232 seven women of Lesbos, skilled in crafts,\u8232 whom I chose for myself when he captured\u8232 well-built Lesbos. They surpass all women\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[130]\u8232 for their beauty. These I shall present to him.\u8232 With them the one I seized from him, Briseis,\u8232 daughter of Briseus. I\'92ll solemnly swear\u8232 I never once went up into her bed\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0160\u8232 or had sex with her, as is men\'92s custom,\u8232 where men and women are concerned.\u8232 All these things he will receive immediately.\u8232 If gods grant we destroy Priam\'92s great city,\u8232 when we Achaeans allocate the spoils,\u8232 let him come and load his ship with gold,\u8232 with bronze, as much as he desires. He may choose\u8232 twenty Trojan women for himself,\u8232 the loveliest after Argive Helen.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[140]\u8232 If we get back to the rich land of Argos,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0170\u8232 he can then become my son-in-law.\u8232 I\'92ll honour him just as I do Orestes,\u8232 my son, whom I dearly love. He\'92s being raised\u8232 in great prosperity. In my well-built home,\u8232 I have three daughters\'97Chrysothemis,\u8232 Iphianessa and Laodice.\u8232 He can take whichever one he chooses\u8232 back home as his wife to Peleus\'92 house\u8232 and pay no bridal gift. I\'92ll give much more\u8232 to bring about our reconciliation,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0180\u8232 a dowry bigger than any man so far\u8232 has ever handed over with his daughter.\u8232 I\'92ll give him seven populous cities,\u8232 Cardamyle, Enope, grassy Hire,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0