\'93Divinely born son of Laertes,\uc0\u8232 resourceful Odysseus. I must be blunt\u8232 about what I think, where all this will lead,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[310]\u8232 so you do not sit there and, one by one,\u8232 try to entice me with sweet promises.\u8232 I hate like the gates of Hell any man\u8232 who says one thing while thinking something else\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0390\u8232 which stays hidden in his mind. So I\'92ll declare\u8232 what, in my view, it\'92s best for me to say\'97\u8232 I don\'92t believe that Agamemnon,\u8232 Atreus\'92 son, or any other Argive\u8232 will persuade me, for no thanks are given\u8232 to the man who always fights without rest\u8232 against the enemy. Whether one fights\u8232 or stays behind, the shares are still the same\u8232 Coward and brave man both get equal honour.\u8232 Death treats idle and active men alike.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0400\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[320]\u8232 I\'92ve won nothing for all I\'92ve suffered,\u8232 battling on, pain in my heart, with my life\u8232 always under threat. Just as a bird\u8232 takes scraps of food, whatever she can find,\u8232 to her fledglings, but herself eats little,\u8232 so have I lain without sleep many nights,\u8232 persevered through bloody days of fighting,\u8232 in battling men in wars about their wives.\u8232 With ships, I\'92ve seized twelve towns and killed their men.\u8232 On land, in the area of fertile Troy,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0410\u8232 I claim eleven more. From all these\u8232 I took fine treasure, lots of it, brought it\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[330]\u8232 to Agamemnon, Atreus\'92 son\'97I gave it\u8232 all to him. He stayed back, at the swift ships.\u8232 He shared very little of what he got,\u8232 keeping most of it for his own use.\u8232 He gave prizes to the best of men, the kings,\u8232 and they hung on to them. From me alone\u8232 he stole away a prize, a woman I love.\u8232 Let him have his pleasure in bed with her.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0420\u8232 Why must Argives fight against the Trojans?\u8232 Why did Atreus\'92 son collect an army\u8232 and lead it here if not for fair-haired Helen?\u8232 Are Atreus\'92 sons the only mortal men\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[340]\u8232 who love their wives? Every good and prudent man\u8232 loves his wife and cares for her, as my heart\u8232 loved that girl, though captured with my spear.\u8232 Since he\'92s taken my prize out of my hands\u8232 and cheated me, let him not try to take\u8232 another thing from me. I know him too well.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0430\u8232 He\'92ll never persuade me to agree.\u8232 But, Odysseus, let him rely on you\u8232 and other kings as well to save his ships\u8232 from fiery destruction. He has done much\u8232 without me already. He\'92s built a wall,\u8232 constructed a large wide ditch around it,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[350]\u8232 and fixed stakes inside. But for all these things,\u8232 he\'92s not been able to check the power\u8232 of man-killing Hector. When I fought\u8232 beside Achaeans, Hector wasn\'92t eager\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0440\u8232 to push the battle far from his own walls.\u8232 He came out only to the Scaean Gates\u8232 and to the oak tree. Once he met me there\u8232 alone. He barely got away from my attack.\u8232 But now I don\'92t want to fight lord Hector.\u8232 Tomorrow I\'92ll make holy sacrifice\u8232 to Zeus, to all the gods, and load my ships,\u8232 once I\'92ve dragged them down into the sea.\u8232 You\'92ll see, if you wish, if you\'92re interested,\u8232 tomorrow my ships will be sailing off,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0450\u8232 on the fish-filled Hellespont, men rowing\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[360]\u8232 with great eagerness. And if Poseidon,\u8232 famous Earthshaker, gives us fair sailing,\u8232 in three days I\'92ll reach fertile Phthia.\u8232 There I own many things I left behind\u8232 when I made this disastrous trip to Troy.\u8232 I\'92ll take back from here more gold, red bronze,\u8232 fair women, and grey iron\'97all I captured.\u8232 But mighty Agamemnon, Atreus\'92 son,\u8232 in his arrogance, seized back from me\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0460\u8232 the prize which he awarded. Tell him that.\u8232 Repeat in public everything I say,\u8232 so other Achaeans will grow angry,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[370]\u8232 if he, still clothed in shamelessness, hopes\u8232 at any time to deceive some Argive.\u8232 Cur that he is, he doesn\'92t dare confront me\u8232 face to face. I\'92ll discuss no plans with him,\u8232 no actions. He cheated me, betrayed me.\u8232 His words will cheat no more. To hell with him!\u8232 Let him march to his death by his own road,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0470\u8232 for Counsellor Zeus has stolen his wits.\u8232 I hate his gifts. And he\'92s not worth a damn.\u8232 Not even if he gave me ten times, no,\u8232 twenty times more than all he owns right now,\u8232 or will possess in future, not even\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[380]\u8232 all the wealth amassed in Orchomenus,\u8232 or Egyptian Thebes, where huge treasures sit\u8232 piled up in houses\'97that city of gates,\u8232 one hundred of them, through each can ride\u8232 two hundred men, horses and chariots\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0480\u8232 all together\'97not even if he gave me\u8232 gifts as numerous as grains of sand\u8232 beside the sea or particles of dust,\u8232 not for all that would Agamemnon win\u8232 my heart, not until he satisfies me\u8232 in full for all my heartfelt bitter pain.\u8232 I\'92ll never take as wife any daughter\u8232 of Agamemnon, son of Atreus,\u8232 not even if her beauty rivals that\u8232 of golden Aphrodite, or her skill\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0490\u8232 in crafts equals bright-eyed Athena\'92s.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[390]\u8232 I will not marry her. Let him select\u8232 another Achaean, someone like himself,\u8232 a more prestigious king than me. For me,\u8232 if the gods keep me safe and I get home,\u8232 Peleus himself will find me a wife.\u8232 There are plenty of Achaean women\u8232 in Hellas and in Phthia\'97daughters of lords,\u8232 men who govern cities. From them I\'92ll choose\u8232 the one I want to make my cherished wife.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0500\u8232 My heart has often felt a strong desire\u8232 to take a woman there as my own wife,\u8232 someone suitable for marriage, to enjoy\u8232 the riches which old Peleus has acquired.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[400]\u8232 Life is worth more to me than all the wealth\u8232 they say was stored in well-built Ilion\u8232 some time ago, when they were still at peace,\u8232 before the sons of Achaea came here,\u8232 more than all the treasures of the archer,\u8232 Phoebus Apollo, stacked on the stone floor\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0510\u8232 in rocky Pytho. Men can steal cattle,\u8232 fat sheep, get tripods, herds of sorrel horses.\u8232 But no man gets his life back, not by theft\u8232 or plunder, once it has flown out from him,\u8232 passed beyond the barrier of his teeth.\u8232 My goddess mother, silver-footed Thetis,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[410]\u8232 has said two fates may bring about my death.\u8232 If I remain here, continuing the fight\u8232 against the Trojans\'92 city, that means\u8232 I won\'92t be going home, but my glory\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0520\u8232 will never die. But if I go back home,\u8232 my fame will die, although my life will last\u8232 a long time\'97death will not end it quickly.\u8232 And so I encourage all the rest of you\u8232 to sail back home. You\'92ll not attain your goal,\u8232 steep Ilion, because far-seeing Zeus\u8232 shields that city with his hand. Its people\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[420]\u8232 have confidence in that. Thus, you should go.\u8232 Report this message to Achaean leaders\'97\u8232 that\'92s the privilege of senior men\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0530\u8232 their minds must come up with some better plan\u8232 to save the Achaean fleet and army\u8232 beside the hollow ships. The one they\'92ve got\u8232 won\'92t work, since anger still keeps me away.\u8232 Let Phoenix stay here with me, sleep here,\u8232 so tomorrow he may join our voyage\u8232 to his dear native land, if that\'92s his wish.\u8232 For I will not take him back by force.\'94\
Achilles spoke. Astounded by his speech, they all sat there,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[430]\uc0\u8232 in silence, stunned by the sheer force of his refusal.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0540\u8232 After a pause, old horseman Phoenix spoke:\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'93Glorious Achilles, if your mind\uc0\u8232 is really set on going back, if you\u8232 are totally unwilling to protect\u8232 our swift ships from destructive fire,\u8232 because that anger has consumed your heart,\u8232 how can I remain here, dear lad, alone,\u8232 away from you? Old horseman Peleus\u8232 sent me with you, on that day he shipped you\u8232 from Phthia to join Agamemnon.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0550\u8232 You were young, knowing nothing about war,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[440]\u8232 which levels men, or about public debates,\u8232 where men acquire distinction. So Peleus\u8232 sent me to teach you all these things,\u8232 so you could speak and carry out great actions.\u8232 Given all this, dear lad, how can I wish\u8232 to be alone and separated from you?\u8232 No, not even if god himself promised\u8232 to cast off my old age, to make me young,\u8232 the man I was when I first left Hellas,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0560\u8232 land of beautiful women, running off\u8232 from my angry father, Amyntor,\u8232 Ormenus\'92 son. He was incensed with me\u8232 about his fair-haired mistress. He loved her,\u8232 thus dishonouring his wife, my mother,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[450]\u8232 who begged me constantly\'97on her knees\'97\u8232 to have sex with that mistress, so she\'92d hate\u8232 my father. I obeyed, did what she asked.\u8232 My father soon found out what I had done\'97\u8232 he cursed me many times repeatedly,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0570\u8232 praying to dread Furies that no dear son\u8232 born from me would ever sit upon his knees.\u8232 The gods made sure his curses took effect,\u8232 underworld Zeus and dread Persephone.\u8232 I planned to murder him with my sharp bronze.\u8232 Some god checked my anger, putting in my heart\u8232 what men would say, their great contempt\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[460]\'a0\'a0\u8232 how among all Achaeans I\'92d be called\u8232 the man who\'92d slaughtered his own father.\u8232 My heart no longer felt the slightest wish\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0580\u8232 to stay in my father\'92s house with him so angry.\u8232 My friends and relatives who lived around me\u8232 begged me repeatedly to stay right there.\u8232 And then they butchered many well-fed sheep,\u8232 shuffling cattle with crumpled horns, and laid out\u8232 many hogs, swimming in fat, to be singed\u8232 in Hephaestus\'92 flames. They drank many jugs\u8232 of the old man\'92s wine. For nine nights,\u8232 they kept watch over me throughout the night,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[470]\u8232 taking turns as guards. Fires always burned,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0590\u8232 one underneath the enclosed portico,\u8232 another in the hallway right outside\u8232 my bedroom doors. Ten nights later, as night fell,\u8232 I broke through the tight-closed bedroom doors,\u8232 went out, and jumped with ease across the wall\u8232 around the outer court, without being seen\u8232 by men and women checking up on me.\u8232 I ran away through all of spacious Hellas,\u8232 then came a suppliant to fertile Phthia,\u8232 where flocks are bred, to king Peleus.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0600\u8232 He received me hospitably, loved me,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[480]\u8232 as a father dearly loves his only son,\u8232 heir to all his goods. He made me wealthy,\u8232 assigning me to govern many people.\u8232 I lived in the borderlands of Phthia,\u8232 reigning as king over the Dolopes.\u8232 And I was the one, godlike Achilles,\u8232 who raised you up to be the man you are.\u8232 You would refuse to attend a banquet\u8232 with anyone or eat in your own home,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0610\u8232 unless I set you on my knees, fed you,\u8232 cut the meat, and held the wine cup for you.\u8232 Often you soaked the tunic on my chest,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[490]\u8232 slobbering your wine, a helpless baby.\u8232 I\'92ve gone through a lot for you, worked hard,\u8232 bearing in mind that gods had taken care\u8232 I\'92d never have some children of my own.\u8232 Godlike Achilles, I made you my son,\u8232 so that if I ever met disaster,\u8232 you\'92d protect me. So, Achilles, subdue\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0620\u8232 your giant passion. It\'92s not right for you\u8232 to have an unyielding heart. Gods themselves\u8232 are flexible, and they have more honour\u8232 than we possess, more power, too. Men pray\u8232 when they go wrong or make mistakes,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[500]\u8232 propitiating gods with offerings,\u8232 gentle prayers, libations, and sacrifice.\u8232 Prayers are the daughters of almighty Zeus.\u8232 Lame, wrinkled, cross-eyed, they try to follow\u8232 behind Folly, who, because she\'92s strong and quick,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0630\u8232 runs far in front of them, appearing\u8232 all over the world, bringing harm to men.\u8232 Far behind, Prayers carry on their healing.\u8232 If a man honours these daughters of Zeus\u8232 as they come near, they will help him greatly,\u8232 paying attention to him as he prays.\u8232 If someone spurns them, rudely rejecting them,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[510]\u8232 they go to Zeus, son of Cronos, begging\u8232 for Folly to pursue that man, who then\u8232 harms himself and suffers punishment.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0640\u8232 For that reason, Achilles, you should give\u8232 Zeus\'92 daughters your respect. They have changed\u8232 the minds of other men, even great ones.\u8232 If Agamemnon were not bringing gifts\'97\u8232 and naming more to come\'97but persisting,\u8232 inflexibly angry, I wouldn\'92t tell you\u8232 to cast aside your rage and help the Argives,\u8232 no matter how painful their distress.\u8232 But he\'92s giving plenty now, more later.\u8232 He has sent out his greatest warriors,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0650\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[520]\u8232 selected from the whole Achaean army,\u8232 your finest friends among the Argives.\u8232 Don\'92t show contempt for what they have to say\u8232 or insult their coming here. Up to now,\u8232 your resentment has been justified.\u8232 But we learn this from previous actions\u8232 of heroic men\'97when furious anger\u8232 came over some of them, they were swayed\u8232 by gifts and by persuasive speeches.\u8232 I recall an old tale from long ago.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0660\u8232 Since you are all my friends, I\'92ll tell it.\u8232 The Curetes and staunch Aetolians\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 were fighting and killing one another,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[530]\u8232 around Calydon, with the Aetolians\u8232 defending Calydon and the Curetes\u8232 eager to destroy the place in war.\u8232 Golden-throned Artemis had driven them to fight,\u8232 in her rage that Oeneus hadn\'92t given her\u8232 a harvest-offering, first fruits of his orchard.\u8232 Other gods had received their sacrifices,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0670\u8232 but he\'92d failed to offer anything to her,\u8232 a daughter of great Zeus. He forgot, or else\u8232 grew careless, a lapse within his foolish heart.\u8232 The archer goddess, in her rage, incited\u8232 a savage white-tusked wild boar against him.\u8232 This beast from the gods reached Oeneus\'92 orchard\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[540]\u8232 and was causing serious damage there,\u8232 knocking tall plants to the ground, entire trees,\u8232 including roots and flowering apples.\u8232 Meleager, Oeneus\'92 son, killed the beast.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0680\u8232 First he gathered huntsmen and hunting dogs\u8232 from many cities, for a small group\u8232 could not subdue such an enormous boar.\u8232 It had killed many men and sent them off\u8232 to their funeral pyres in agony.\u8232 Artemis began a war about this beast,\u8232 that battle between the Curetes\u8232 and the Aetolians, courageous men\u8232 fighting for the boar\'92s head and bristly hide.\u8232 So long as war-loving Meleager\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0690\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[550]\u8232 was in the fight, the Curetes did not do well.\u8232 For all their numbers, they could not hold\u8232 their ground outside the city walls.\u8232 But then anger swept through Meleager,\u8232 just as it forcibly swells up in chests\u8232 of other men, including wise ones, too.\u8232 His heart was angry with his dear mother,\u8232 Althea. So he stayed home with his wife,\u8232 Cleopatra, the attractive daughter\u8232 of the lady with the lovely ankles,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0700\u8232 Maripessa, daughter of Euenus\u8232 and Ides, strongest of all men then alive.\u8232 He was the one who took his bow to make\u8232 a stand against a god, Phoebus Apollo,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[560]\u8232 fighting for the girl with lovely ankles.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 Cleopatra\'92s father and noble mother\u8232 at home called her by the name Alcyone.\u8232 Her mother shared the same fate as that bird,\u8232 the mournful halcyon, for she cried\u8232 when Apollo, the far shooter, seized her.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0710\u8232 Beside this Cleopatra Meleager lay,\u8232 brooding on the rage that pained his heart,\u8232 infuriated by his mother\'92s curses.\u8232 In her grief over her brothers\'92 killing,\u8232 she prayed to the gods, beating fertile earth\u8232 with her hands over and over, kneeling down,\u8232 her breasts wet from crying, begging Hades\u8232 and fearful Persephone to kill her son.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://records.viu.ca/~johnstoi/homer/iliad9.htm#n1"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \strokec2 *}}\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[570]\uc0\u8232 The night-walking Furies, with their stone hearts,\u8232 listened to her prayers from Erebus.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0720\u8232 Then around the gates of Calydon\u8232 the battle din grew loud, war\'92s turmoil.\u8232 The gates were being demolished. The old men\u8232 of the Aetolians begged Meleager\u8232 to come to their assistance. They sent\u8232 their gods\'92 most important holy priests.\u8232 They promised him great gifts, telling him\u8232 he could take for himself, from anywhere\u8232 on the richest plain of lovely Calydon\u8232 fifty acres of the finest farm land,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0730\u8232 half for a vineyard and half for farming,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[580]\u8232 open fields for ploughing. Oeneus,\u8232 the old horseman, kept imploring him,\u8232 standing at the threshold of his high room,\u8232 beating on the firmly bolted doors,\u8232 begging his son. His sisters and his mother\u8232 often entreated him. But he refused.\u8232 His companions, those most faithful to him,\u8232 his closest friends of all, added their prayers.\u8232 But they could not overcome those passions\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0740\u8232 in his chest, not until his own room\u8232 was under fierce attack, once the Curetes\u8232 had scaled the tower and 